/* 1855_grail_meanpayoff_weight_obstruction.iii -- FORMAL WALL, the QUANT-GAMES face's precise obstruction (PROVEN).
 *
 * THEOREM (Mean-Payoff Reduction forces EXPONENTIAL weights).  The standard reduction parity -> mean-payoff /
 * energy / discounted game assigns each vertex a weight by priority so that, on ANY cycle (length <= n), a SINGLE
 * occurrence of the highest priority p outweighs every lower priority combined (this "priority-separating" property
 * is exactly what makes sign(cycle-sum) = parity(max priority), i.e. what makes the reduction correct).  The MINIMAL
 * such magnitudes grow GEOMETRICALLY:
 *     w(0) = 1,   w(p) = 1 + n * sum_{q<p} w(q)   =>   w(p) = (n+1) * w(p-1)   =>   w(p) = (n+1)^p.
 * Hence the top weight w(d) = (n+1)^d is EXPONENTIAL in the number of priorities d, the induced mean-payoff/energy
 * values need Theta(d log n) bits, and value iteration over them is only PSEUDO-polynomial (polynomial in the value
 * MAGNITUDE, which is exponential in d).
 *
 * SIGNIFICANCE.  This is the precise, formal reason the whole QUANT-GAMES / ENERGY / LP / DISCOUNTED branch of
 * Class II (the parity-novel-invent survivors ENERGY-DISJ, ENERGY-VARWEIGHT, DISCOUNT-HOMOTOPY, TROPICAL-SPECTRAL)
 * inherits the difficulty rather than dissolving it: parity DOES reduce to mean-payoff (an equivalence-web face,
 * DOCS/III-PARITY-WALL-FORMAL.md Sec 5), but the reduction is forced to carry exponential-magnitude numbers, so a
 * polynomial mean-payoff algorithm would have to be poly in the BIT-LENGTH (strongly polynomial / sign-only), which
 * is itself open.  The numbers are where the alternation hides in this face.
 *
 * VERIFICATION.  Compute the minimal priority-separating weights for several n and verify (a) the geometric identity
 * w(p) = (n+1)*w(p-1) exactly, (b) the closed form w(d) = (n+1)^d, and (c) the bit-length of w(d) grows linearly
 * with d (i.e. magnitude is exponential), in contrast to a polynomial encoding which would need O(log d) bits.
 * exit 99 = the exponential-weight obstruction holds for every n, d sampled. */
module mmpo
var W : [u64; 32]

fn bitlen(x: u64) -> u32 { let mut v : u64 = x  let mut b : u32 = 0u32  while v != 0u64 { b = b + 1u32  v = v >> 1u64 }  return b }
fn ipow(base: u64, e: u32) -> u64 { let mut r : u64 = 1u64  let mut i : u32 = 0u32  while i < e { r = r * base  i = i + 1u32 }  return r }

fn main() -> u64 {
    let mut n : u64 = 3u64
    while n <= 8u64 {
        let d : u32 = 11u32                          /* priorities 0..11 (keeps (n+1)^d within u64 for n<=8) */
        /* minimal priority-separating weights: w(0)=1, w(p)=1 + n*sum_{q<p} w(q) */
        W[0u64] = 1u64
        let mut acc : u64 = W[0u64]                  /* running sum_{q<=p} */
        let mut p : u32 = 1u32
        while p <= d {
            W[p as u64] = 1u64 + n * (acc)           /* exceed n copies of every lower priority */
            /* (a) geometric identity: w(p) == (n+1)*w(p-1) */
            if W[p as u64] != (n + 1u64) * W[(p - 1u32) as u64] { return 10u64 }
            acc = acc + W[p as u64]
            p = p + 1u32
        }
        /* (b) closed form: w(d) == (n+1)^d */
        if W[d as u64] != ipow(n + 1u64, d) { return 11u64 }
        /* (c) EXPONENTIAL magnitude: bit-length of w(d) grows ~ d*log2(n+1); for n>=3 that is >= 2*d -- linear in d.
         * A POLYNOMIAL-magnitude encoding would have bit-length O(log d); we are far above that. */
        let bl : u32 = bitlen(W[d as u64])
        if bl < 2u32 * d { return 12u64 }            /* bitlen(w(d)) >= 2d (n>=3 => log2(n+1) >= 2) -> exponential */
        n = n + 1u64
    }
    return 99u64
}
